And in that time, they really struggled hard to eventually reach

102
00:06:06,729 --> 00:06:08,529
this big success that they've reached now.

103
00:06:09,310 --> 00:06:12,611
After so many years of working and making games, they finally hit something big.

104
00:06:13,192 --> 00:06:16,973
And right now, I'd just like to take a moment to congratulate the Art Director of

105
00:06:16,973 --> 00:06:19,175
Massive Monster, James Pearmain, who's here with us.

106
00:06:22,616 --> 00:06:27,699
It's such an amazing achievement to work all those years with a small team to reach this

107
00:06:27,759 --> 00:06:31,741
point and giving me the chance to speak on behalf of the team here.

108
00:06:31,841 --> 00:06:32,716
Thank you, James.

109
00:06:33,962 --> 00:06:34,532
Thank you.

110
00:06:35,382 --> 00:06:37,525
Before we get into the weeds of the talk,

111
00:06:37,525 --> 00:06:40,624
I'm going to give you the big takeaway right at the start.

112
00:06:41,145 --> 00:06:44,006
So if you remember one thing from this talk, this is it.

113
00:06:44,086 --> 00:06:44,966
It's the next slide.

114
00:06:45,026 --> 00:06:47,847
Pay attention right now and you don't have to pay attention for the rest.

115
00:06:48,408 --> 00:06:49,968
Games go viral.

116
00:06:50,328 --> 00:06:55,511
And what I mean by that is that the biggest factor to selling your game is your game.

117
00:06:58,192 --> 00:06:58,932
Take a photo.

118
00:06:58,932 --> 00:06:59,682
Nice.

119
00:07:01,333 --> 00:07:03,762
We're not talking about if your game is good,

120
00:07:03,762 --> 00:07:06,336
because there's really so many good games out there,

121
00:07:06,336 --> 00:07:09,077
and good is subjective, and like, who really knows what's good?

122
00:07:09,903 --> 00:07:14,060
And really, you're even competing with every other thing that someone could do in their life.

123
00:07:14,360 --> 00:07:18,222
As Nick said earlier this week, touching grass is better than most games.

124
00:07:19,242 --> 00:07:20,463
And I wholeheartedly agree.

125
00:07:20,903 --> 00:07:22,263
So you really got to ask yourself,

126
00:07:22,563 --> 00:07:24,624
is your game truly outstanding?

127
00:07:24,664 --> 00:07:27,665
And by that I mean, does your game stand out?

128
00:07:28,005 --> 00:07:30,566
How does it compare to not just every other game out there,

129
00:07:30,606 --> 00:07:32,087
which is already so many things,

130
00:07:32,347 --> 00:07:35,028
but every other thing that someone could be doing in their lives?

131
00:07:35,268 --> 00:07:36,788
That's literally what you're competing with

132
00:07:36,868 --> 00:07:38,849
when we're talking about trying to get someone to play

133
00:07:38,869 --> 00:07:40,530
whatever little game that you're working on.

134
00:07:42,595 --> 00:07:46,238
The biggest factor behind Cult of the Lamb's success is the work of these guys.

135
00:07:46,718 --> 00:07:50,980
They weren't thinking at the start, how can our game go viral?

136
00:07:51,581 --> 00:07:55,083
They were thinking, how can our game be fun and memorable?

137
00:07:55,563 --> 00:07:58,885
And along the way, they made something that I think did all of that.

138
00:08:01,040 --> 00:08:02,941
I think the keyword there is memorable.

139
00:08:03,381 --> 00:08:08,623
There's an old marketing rule of thumb called the seven touch points, where it takes an

140
00:08:08,763 --> 00:08:12,825
average of seven touch points for a potential buyer to make a purchasing decision.

141
00:08:13,365 --> 00:08:14,786
And what is a touch point?

142
00:08:15,246 --> 00:08:19,788
Well, here are some examples, but basically it's any time someone encounters your thing,

143
00:08:20,449 --> 00:08:23,950
in this case, your game, or in our case today, our cult.

144
00:08:25,208 --> 00:08:28,470
Whenever, anytime they see anything related to it,

145
00:08:28,770 --> 00:08:31,452
so whether that's on a store shelf or a physical product

146
00:08:31,712 --> 00:08:34,754
or on a billboard or on a radio ad for the boomers

147
00:08:35,214 --> 00:08:39,497
or on social media or someone is telling you about it

148
00:08:39,537 --> 00:08:40,917
or your friend is telling you about it,

149
00:08:40,978 --> 00:08:42,779
all of those are possible touch points.

150
00:08:43,759 --> 00:08:46,061
And each time they see your thing,

151
00:08:46,081 --> 00:08:48,002
whether that's through a streamer or an article

152
00:08:48,022 --> 00:08:50,503
or on social media, they're one step closer

153
00:08:50,543 --> 00:08:52,084
to potentially buying your thing.

154
00:08:53,075 --> 00:08:57,377
That's why at Devolver we try to push all of these channels as much as possible

155
00:08:57,637 --> 00:09:00,019
so that we get as many touch points into people's eyes

156
00:09:00,399 --> 00:09:02,120
and eventually maybe they will buy something.

157
00:09:02,920 --> 00:09:06,443
There are so many channels to pursue and whether you're a small indie

158
00:09:06,783 --> 00:09:08,744
or you're from a big publisher or a big company,

159
00:09:09,384 --> 00:09:10,905
I'm pretty sure you're probably thinking,

160
00:09:11,886 --> 00:09:15,428
how do we find which of these channels is the best ones to aim for?

161
00:09:15,788 --> 00:09:19,670
Which ones is the best one to allocate our limited time, money, and budget?

162
00:09:20,794 --> 00:09:24,475
So, I'm going to tell you a bit about my little corner, which is social media.

163
00:09:24,875 --> 00:09:27,976
There's definitely certain benefits to using it as one of your primary channels.

164
00:09:28,656 --> 00:09:31,777
Number one, it's low cost compared to some of the other ones,

165
00:09:32,457 --> 00:09:34,598
because anyone can post something for free.

166
00:09:35,098 --> 00:09:37,458
Number two, it has exponential potential.

167
00:09:37,798 --> 00:09:40,139
It's built upon people interacting and resharing,

168
00:09:40,159 --> 00:09:42,820
and those things are inherently built into these platforms.

169
00:09:43,320 --> 00:09:48,602
And number three, since it's built on those connections, it's kind of like a pseudo word of mouth.

170
00:09:48,907 --> 00:09:51,010
When you see your friend retweet something,

171
00:09:51,010 --> 00:09:54,954
then that's a pseudo endorsement from them about whatever they've just retweeted.

172
00:09:55,205 --> 00:09:57,966
And you have a bit of that trust, and if any marketing people here will know,

173
00:09:58,046 --> 00:10:00,707
word of mouth is by far the strongest touchpoint that you can have.

174
00:10:02,388 --> 00:10:07,350
So, you're probably also wondering, does social media actually convert to anything?

175
00:10:08,601 --> 00:10:12,244
For example, if I somehow win the lottery with a viral post,

176
00:10:12,645 --> 00:10:15,367
will it actually lead to tangible sales or wish lists

177
00:10:15,407 --> 00:10:16,808
or whatever kind of metric you're looking at?

178
00:10:17,829 --> 00:10:21,753
Well, the answer is sometimes.

179
00:10:22,213 --> 00:10:23,074
Definitely not always.

180
00:10:23,674 --> 00:10:26,257
The secret to big sales is making an outstanding game,

181
00:10:26,277 --> 00:10:27,037
like I said before.

182
00:10:27,558 --> 00:10:31,130
But that doesn't always mean having a very unique art style

183
00:10:31,130 --> 00:10:33,363
or the best game or awards or anything like that.

184
00:10:35,095 --> 00:10:38,016
Here's an example that I love, Vampire Survivors.

185
00:10:38,316 --> 00:10:41,737
It is outstandingly fun to play.

186
00:10:42,218 --> 00:10:45,119
It keeps people in Steam and spending money on Steam,

187
00:10:45,379 --> 00:10:47,500
so then Steam keeps pushing it to more people.

188
00:10:48,060 --> 00:10:49,481
Sales platforms, they make money

189
00:10:49,721 --> 00:10:51,281
when things are sold on their platform,

190
00:10:51,522 --> 00:10:53,382
so then their algorithms promote things

191
00:10:53,482 --> 00:10:54,703
that are more likely to sell.

192
00:10:55,043 --> 00:10:56,083
It's really that simple.

193
00:10:56,544 --> 00:10:58,344
So then if they're pushing you,

194
00:10:58,704 --> 00:11:01,886
then you get a sale, you get your portion,

195
00:11:01,966 --> 00:11:03,186
they get their cut, and...

196
00:11:03,887 --> 00:11:06,435
People are happy, except for the people who didn't get sales, sorry.

197
00:11:08,811 --> 00:11:12,294
So another question, how can I be outstanding?

198
00:11:12,694 --> 00:11:15,036
Outstanding doesn't have to be entirely new.

199
00:11:16,277 --> 00:11:18,139
I think we can all think of lots of games

200
00:11:18,219 --> 00:11:21,282
