00:13:30,487 --> 00:13:32,771
I think it's developed by two people. That's ridiculous.

243
00:13:33,950 --> 00:13:37,142
And finally, this is from Hypercharge, a two-year-old game

244
00:13:37,142 --> 00:13:40,371
that got a bunch of new life after they went viral on Twitter last summer.

245
00:13:41,231 --> 00:13:42,492
And there's other examples too.

246
00:13:42,872 --> 00:13:48,393
We can think of something like Choo Choo Charles or Trombone Champ, all that have released

247
00:13:48,393 --> 00:13:50,705
very recently and are relatively small games,

248
00:13:50,705 --> 00:13:53,914
and they got most of their buzz through social media.

249
00:13:54,234 --> 00:13:57,635
So there are examples of social media playing a big role in game success.

250
00:13:59,090 --> 00:14:02,133
But social media is just one of these channels.

251
00:14:02,674 --> 00:14:05,916
At Devolver, we try to leverage all of the channels as best as we can.

252
00:14:06,557 --> 00:14:11,601
Cult of the Lamp had a truly astounding reception from influencers

253
00:14:11,907 --> 00:14:15,390
through a strategy from our senior influencer strategist, Clara Sia.

254
00:14:16,165 --> 00:14:20,588
As well as a truly awesome Twitch integration made by Streaming Toolsmith,

255
00:14:20,648 --> 00:14:24,529
who has been around at GDC if you want to work with him to implement Twitch integration.

256
00:14:25,070 --> 00:14:27,951
It was also at things like Summer Games Fest.

257
00:14:28,131 --> 00:14:29,612
We brought it to PAX East last year.

258
00:14:29,672 --> 00:14:31,293
It's at PAX East this year right now.

259
00:14:31,713 --> 00:14:32,953
It was in Steam Next Fest.

260
00:14:33,474 --> 00:14:38,996
But all of these contributed to what the game's marketing was.

261
00:14:40,187 --> 00:14:43,068
And all of them came together to support, most importantly,

262
00:14:43,448 --> 00:14:45,869
an outstanding game made by Massive Monster.

263
00:14:46,429 --> 00:14:50,191
And yes, my little corner of that big equation is just social media.

264
00:14:50,491 --> 00:14:51,711
So that's what I'm going to talk about.

265
00:14:53,192 --> 00:14:55,093
We're talking here about attention.

266
00:14:55,553 --> 00:14:57,033
Attention is marketing currency.

267
00:14:57,113 --> 00:15:00,174
And like I said before, people have limited time and attention in their lives.

268
00:15:00,194 --> 00:15:02,215
You're competing with any other thing that someone could do.

269
00:15:02,615 --> 00:15:06,296
So how are you going to make the most of whatever tiny bit of attention they might give you?

270
00:15:07,893 --> 00:15:10,555
And these are my three steps of content design.

271
00:15:11,075 --> 00:15:13,757
Number one, grab attention for discovery.

272
00:15:14,357 --> 00:15:16,819
Number two, convert attention into interest.

273
00:15:17,159 --> 00:15:19,160
And number three, reward attention

274
00:15:19,280 --> 00:15:20,761
with an emotional response.

275
00:15:21,041 --> 00:15:22,883
I'm going to go into detail about each of these,

276
00:15:23,263 --> 00:15:26,505
as well as talking about how the original design

277
00:15:26,865 --> 00:15:29,187
by the Massive Monster guys played into this,

278
00:15:29,587 --> 00:15:33,650
and then how I try to implement these on Twitter, TikTok,

279
00:15:33,910 --> 00:15:36,091
and then how it applies to even the Steam store page.

280
00:15:36,131 --> 00:15:37,552
So anywhere they can see your thing.

281
00:15:37,812 --> 00:15:39,294
These are things that you should be thinking about.

282
00:15:41,416 --> 00:15:44,819
So number one, grab attention for discovery.

283
00:15:46,300 --> 00:15:47,161
Start your own cult.

284
00:15:47,821 --> 00:15:50,124
I think that is pretty attention grabbing for a game.

285
00:15:50,804 --> 00:15:53,447
Before they click on your thing, before they watch your thing,

286
00:15:53,467 --> 00:15:55,408
when someone is just scrolling down their timeline,

287
00:15:55,669 --> 00:15:57,130
what actually grabs their attention?

288
00:15:57,190 --> 00:15:59,272
What grabs your attention when you're scrolling down the timeline?

289
00:15:59,572 --> 00:16:01,634
What makes you stop and read or watch?

290
00:16:02,695 --> 00:16:06,897
Some things that usually work are things like eye-catching visuals or surprising messages.

291
00:16:07,237 --> 00:16:08,558
Here's one of my examples.

292
00:16:09,038 --> 00:16:12,259
Cults of the Lamb does not support hashtag national boyfriend day.

293
00:16:12,619 --> 00:16:16,201
Why have one boyfriend when you can have several spouses?

294
00:16:19,042 --> 00:16:22,804
So, I try to get into what I call a noob mindset.

295
00:16:23,144 --> 00:16:27,006
What does it look like to someone who doesn't know anything about your game?

296
00:16:28,080 --> 00:16:30,225
Because if they already know about your game, then you probably don't...

297
00:16:30,726 --> 00:16:33,613
You do kind of need to sell it to them, because maybe they haven't bought it yet.

298
00:16:33,954 --> 00:16:37,522
But more importantly, how do you make it visible to people who have no idea what it is?

299
00:16:39,527 --> 00:16:42,428
So, Massive Monster, they thought about this idea

300
00:16:42,488 --> 00:16:43,588
of a four-word pitch.

301
00:16:44,168 --> 00:16:46,648
Their previous two games were 2D platformers

302
00:16:46,688 --> 00:16:48,149
where you play as a little guy.

303
00:16:49,269 --> 00:16:51,229
They weren't bad games, but you could probably tell

304
00:16:51,249 --> 00:16:53,190
that that concept doesn't really stand out.

305
00:16:54,110 --> 00:16:56,550
They came up, instead, they came up with an idea

306
00:16:56,830 --> 00:17:00,451
of merging two popular genres, roguelike and base building.

307
00:17:00,851 --> 00:17:03,811
And with that in mind, they tried to build a player fantasy

308
00:17:03,951 --> 00:17:05,672
around that core gameplay loop.

309
00:17:06,572 --> 00:17:07,892
The fantasy had to be unique.

310
00:17:08,660 --> 00:17:10,681
Appealing and easy to explain.

311
00:17:11,321 --> 00:17:14,942
And they actually originally had a pitch in 2019

312
00:17:15,262 --> 00:17:20,325
which had a very complex, a much more complex player fantasy.

313
00:17:20,945 --> 00:17:22,906
And instead, eventually they got to this point

314
00:17:23,226 --> 00:17:25,787
where they thought about how easy to explain could it be?

315
00:17:26,327 --> 00:17:27,828
Could it even fit within four words?

316
00:17:28,828 --> 00:17:29,312
Yes.

317
00:17:30,051 --> 00:17:32,853
What about start your own hell or start a witch's coven

318
00:17:32,853 --> 00:17:35,327
and then finally landing on start your own cult?

319
00:17:35,693 --> 00:17:38,514
Can you explain what you're working on in just four words?

320
00:17:42,316 --> 00:17:45,017
So here are some examples. We're going to watch some TikToks.

321
00:17:47,418 --> 00:17:49,258
Have you ever considered joining a cult?

322
00:17:49,959 --> 00:17:53,880
It's a great place to make friends, have fun, and eat some tasty food.

323
00:17:55,931 --> 00:17:58,752
There's a few folks who don't really agree with how we do things,

324
00:17:59,313 --> 00:18:02,614
but that's why we show them love to change their minds.

325
00:18:03,255 --> 00:18:03,615
Or else.

326
00:18:04,415 --> 00:18:07,497
You can play Cults of the Lem right now on all consoles and PC.

327
00:18:08,517 --> 00:18:09,418
Yeah, nice.

328
00:18:10,148 --> 00:18:11,609
Let's watch this other one.

329
00:18:11,769 --> 00:18:14,570
Sometimes you gotta deal with followers who are trying to trick your cultists.

330
00:18:14,791 --> 00:18:19,213
Talk to them, put them in jail, or maybe use them as a ritual sacrifice.

331
00:18:19,373 --> 00:18:21,474
And here on TikTok, watch out, there's a scammer.

332
00:18:21,574 --> 00:18:24,056
They're messaging people, telling them they won the giveaway,

333
00:18:24,076 --> 00:18:25,497
and asking them to click a link.

334
00:18:25,657 --> 00:18:28,118
Don't click the link. We aren't sending anything like that.

335
00:18:28,758 --> 00:18:32,841
Yeah, if anyone has done a giveaway on TikTok, you know about those scammers.

336
00:18:33,961 --> 00:18:34,382
Okay.

337
00:18:36,403 --> 00:18:38,104
Sometimes you gotta deal with...

338
00:18:38,304 --> 00:18:38,994
Okay.

339
00:18:40,655 --> 00:18:43,136
That is what I feel like when I'm browsing TikTok.

340
00:18:44,956 --> 00:18:48,097
So when you're thinking about discovery on TikTok,

341
00:18:48,237 --> 00:18:50,637
and really discovery anywhere, the first question

342
00:18:50,897 --> 00:18:54,478
is who might see your thing on this platform?

343
00:18:55,338 --> 00:18:58,059
In this case, it's people who trend younger.

344
00:18:58,439 --> 00:18:59,859
And it might sound stupid, but it's

345
00:18:59,939 --> 00:19:01,880
people who already use TikTok.

346
00:19:02,200 --> 00:19:04,120
But what I mean by that is that they

347
00:19:04,140 --> 00:19:06,381
have certain contextual expectations for what

348
00:19:06,401 --> 00:19:07,841
they come across on the app.

349
00:19:08,756 --> 00:19:11,137
And then next, how will they see your content?

350
00:19:11,698 --> 00:19:14,379
TikTok videos automatically show up in your For You page,

351
00:19:14,900 --> 00:19:18,702
and people don't really browse or watch based on who they're already following.

352
00:19:19,622 --> 00:19:21,523
And then finally, what will they actually see?

353
00:19:21,904 --> 00:19:26,166
The video will just start playing, and now your job is to keep them from swiping away.

354
00:19:26,486 --> 00:19:28,743
So yeah, think about these three things

355
00:19:28,743 --> 00:19:31,486
on any kind of platform that you're trying to post anything.

356
00:19:32,600 --> 00:19:33,141
Another here...

357
00:19:34,101 --> 00:19:36,421
Oh, sorry, before we move on, you can see on that retention rate,

358
00:19:36,421 --> 00:19:38,133
that was from the second video we watched,

359
00:19:38,417 --> 00:19:43,644
 more than 25, about 25% of people stopped watching after two seconds.

360
00:19:44,024 --> 00:19:48,465
So that's how much time that you have to convince someone to keep watching your video.

361
00:19:50,666 --> 00:19:53,127
And two seconds is already pretty long.

362
00:19:53,467 --> 00:19:54,307
Steam discovery.

363
00:19:54,647 --> 00:19:57,008
So once again, we're thinking, who is on this platform?

364
00:19:58,051 --> 00:20:00,033
On Steam, you know it's someone who already plays games.

365
00:20:00,593 --> 00:20:01,594
They're playing on PC.

366
00:20:02,214 --> 00:20:04,556
And they are looking for more games to play.

367
00:20:05,076 --> 00:20:08,481
Most people on Steam are not looking for more new games to play.

368
00:20:08,839 --> 00:20:11,201
So you don't really need to think about them.

369
00:20:11,621 --> 00:20:13,543
So these are the people you're thinking about.

370
00:20:13,823 --> 00:20:15,384
And then how can they see your content?

371
00:20:15,904 --> 00:20:17,546
There's algorithmic recommendations,

372
00:20:17,746 --> 00:20:21,028
things that say games you might like or try these.

373
00:20:21,369 --> 00:20:22,730
Steam has stuff like that.

374
00:20:23,230 --> 00:20:25,051
And then also on the front page, if you're

375
00:20:25,071 --> 00:20:27,173
lucky enough to get there or right at your launch time.

376
00:20:28,014 --> 00:20:30,555
And then, what will they actually see when they get there?

377
00:20:31,135 --> 00:20:31,916
So let's take a look.

378
00:20:32,336 --> 00:20:35,778
This is from the fall when Little Gator Game had just released.

379
00:20:38,079 --> 00:20:42,221
So on the left side, that is what you would see on your Steam page without even scrolling over

380
00:20:42,261 --> 00:20:46,984
anything. So look what we have to work with. We have the capsule art, we have the title,

381
00:20:47,404 --> 00:20:54,228
we have the platform, we have four tags, and then we have the price and the sale.

382
00:20:54,648 --> 00:20:56,806
So like that rectangle

383
00:20:56,806 --> 00:20:59,019
is all you have to try to convince someone

384
00:20:59,019 --> 00:21:01,854
to even hover over your game, to consider it at all.

385
00:21:02,314 --> 00:21:04,203
And then if you do manage to convince someone to hover,

386
00:21:04,203 --> 00:21:05,817
then that's where you get the thing on the right,

387
00:21:06,177 --> 00:21:10,027
where now we get to see the number of reviews, the overall rating,

388
00:21:10,027 --> 00:21:11,761
we have one extra tag now,

389
00:21:12,102 --> 00:21:14,687
and three screenshots, or a few screenshots.

390
00:21:14,687 --> 00:21:17,265
So that is the kind of stuff that we're talking about,

391
00:21:17,506 --> 00:21:20,110
of how can you grab someone's attention with just that.

392
00:21:20,552 --> 00:21:23,290
It's almost nothing, and that is how hard

393
00:21:23,350 --> 00:21:25,071
it is to get yourself seen and discovered.

394
00:21:26,847 --> 00:21:30,170
Next, convert attention into interest.

395
00:21:31,250 --> 00:21:33,212
So at this point, you've grabbed their attention.

396
00:21:33,672 --> 00:21:36,794
How do you keep them looking and what are you trying to do with the attention?

397
00:21:37,095 --> 00:21:40,737
What are you going to, what kind of memory are you going to leave them with?

398
00:21:41,277 --> 00:21:44,200
And that's something that the Massive Monster guys really thought about

399
00:21:44,500 --> 00:21:46,041
in what they called trailer moments.

400
00:21:46,341 --> 00:21:50,603
These are moments that they animated and put in the game that look very, very impressive.

401
00:21:50,943 --> 00:21:52,558
Moments that people will remember,

402
00:21:52,558 --> 00:21:55,065
moments that show something interesting about the game.

403
00:21:55,665 --> 00:21:58,827
This is probably one of the more iconic ones that people remember.

404
00:21:58,887 --> 00:22:01,448
If you've played Cult of the Lamb, this is the sacrifice ritual.

405
00:22:01,928 --> 00:22:05,976
There's a part of the game where the game actually makes you do at least one of these,

406
00:22:05,976 --> 00:22:06,810
so you can see it.

407
00:22:07,151 --> 00:22:09,552
And you can see it's like less than 10 seconds.

408
00:22:09,712 --> 00:22:12,094
And how much time do you think you worked on it, James?

